04217nam a22005175i 9780674249776DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20202020mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742497767 a10.4159/97806742497762doi  a(DE-B1597)572464  a(OCoLC)1224279290  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aBR1642.U6 7aHIS0360602bisacsh04a261.8/336097309042231 aGriffith, Aaron, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGod’s Law and Order /cAaron Griffith. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (320 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1 Churchdom’s War on Crime -- t2 Jesus Christ Is the Only Control -- t3 Religion Is a Real Weapon -- t4 God’s Law and Order -- t5 A Sermon in Your Cell -- t6 There Are Better Ways -- tConclusion -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tAcknowledgments -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn incisive look at how evangelical Christians shaped—and were shaped by—the American criminal justice system.America incarcerates on a massive scale. Despite recent reforms, the United States locks up large numbers of people—disproportionately poor and nonwhite—for long periods and offers little opportunity for restoration. Aaron Griffith reveals a key component in the origins of American mass incarceration: evangelical Christianity.Evangelicals in the postwar era made crime concern a major religious issue and found new platforms for shaping public life through punitive politics. Religious leaders like Billy Graham and David Wilkerson mobilized fears of lawbreaking and concern for offenders to sharpen appeals for Christian conversion, setting the stage for evangelicals who began advocating tough-on-crime politics in the 1960s. Building on religious campaigns for public safety earlier in the twentieth century, some preachers and politicians pushed for “law and order,” urging support for harsh sentences and expanded policing. Other evangelicals saw crime as a missionary opportunity, launching innovative ministries that reshaped the practice of religion in prisons. From the 1980s on, evangelicals were instrumental in popularizing criminal justice reform, making it a central cause in the compassionate conservative movement. At every stage in their work, evangelicals framed their efforts as colorblind, which only masked racial inequality in incarceration and delayed real change.Today evangelicals play an ambiguous role in reform, pressing for reduced imprisonment while backing law-and-order politicians. God’s Law and Order shows that we cannot understand the criminal justice system without accounting for evangelicalism’s impact on its historical development.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aChurch and statezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aCriminal justice, Administration ofzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aEvangelicalismzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / 20th Century.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHarvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069005740uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/978067424977640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674249776423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780674249776.jpg  a978-3-11-069005-7  Harvard University Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles